<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,775,1292,1925]" lastBlockId="2.[813,1437,237,1893]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis box="[173,285,1710,1733]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Tis genus is characterized by having a long and slender body, long elytra, acute, convex and partially dehiscent, small head, strongly flattened antero-posteriorly with vertex transversely planar, specialized mouthparts with elongated galea, bilobed ligula covered by bristles, prominent tibial spurs, tibial spur formula 2-2-2, antennae 11-segmented, mesonotal and metanotal legs with erect stiff spiniform setae, pretarsal claws serrate, abdominal segments laterally compressed, apical fields on hind wings with secondary “ghost” branches (sensu [
<bibRefCitation author="Kukalova-Peck J &amp; Lawrence JF" box="[821,847,333,357]" journalOrPublisher="Can Entomol." pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="181 - 258" part="125" refId="ref9774" refString="26. Kukalova-Peck J, Lawrence JF. Evolution of the hind wing in Coleoptera. Can Entomol. 1993; 125: 181 - 258." title="Evolution of the hind wing in Coleoptera" type="journal article" year="1993">26</bibRefCitation>
]: 186) and apices of hind wings asymmetrically overlapping in resting position.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
